"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP10.raw"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP11.raw"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP12.raw"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP2.raw"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP3.raw"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP4.raw"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP5.raw"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP6.raw"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP7.raw"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP8.raw"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000404", "name": "Associated raw file URI", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537/GHD_PSD_Sleep_4TMT_TiO2_Tech_Rep2_bRP9.raw"}], "description": "Homeostatic scaling is a global form of synaptic plasticity used by neurons to adjust overall synaptic weight and maintain neuronal firing rates while protecting information coding. While homeostatic scaling has been demonstrated in vitro, a clear physiological function of this plasticity type has not been defined. Sleep is an essential process that modifies synapses to support cognitive functions such as learning and memory. Evidence suggests that information coding during wake drives synapse strengthening which is offset by weakening of synapses during sleep .Here we use biochemical fractionation, proteomics and in vivo two-photon imaging to characterize wide-spread changes in synapse composition in mice through the wake/sleep cycle. We find that during the sleep phase, synapses are weakened through dephosphorylation and removal of synaptic AMPA-type glutamate receptors (AMPARs) driven by the immediate early gene Homer1a and signaling from group I metabotropic glutamate receptors (mGluR1/5), consistent with known mechanisms of homeostatic scaling-down in vitro. Further, we find that these changes are important in the consolidation of contextual memories. While Homer1a gene expression is driven by neuronal activity during wake, Homer1a protein targeting to synapses serves as an integrator of arousal and sleep need through signaling by the wake-promoting neuromodulator noradrenaline (NA) and sleep-promoting modulator adenosine. During sleep or periods of increased sleep need Homer1a enters synapses where it remodels mGluR1/5 signaling complexes to promote AMPAR removal. Thus, we have characterized widespread changes occurring at synapses through the wake/sleep cycle and demonstrated that known mechanisms of homeostatic scaling-down previously demonstrated only in vitro are active in the brain during sleep to remodel synapses, contributing to memory consolidation.", "fullDatasetLinks": [{"accession": "PRIDE:0000411", "name": "Dataset FTP location", "value": "ftp://ftp.pride.ebi.ac.uk/pride/data/archive/2017/02/PXD004537"}, {"accession": "MS:1001930", "name": "PRIDE project URI", "value": "http://www.ebi.ac.uk/pride/archive/projects/PXD004537"}], "identifiers": [{"accession": "MS:1001919", "name": "ProteomeXchange accession number", "value": "PXD004537"}], "instruments": [{"accession": "MS:1002417", "name": "Orbitrap Fusion ETD"}], "keywords": [{"accession": "MS:1001925", "name": "submitter keyword", "value": "Sleep, Homer1A, Phosphoproteomics"}, {"accession": "MS:1001926", "name": "curator keyword", "value": "Biological"}, {"accession": "MS:1001926", "name": "curator keyword", "value": "Biomedical"}], "modifications": [{"accession": "MOD:01720", "name": "TMT6plex-126 reporter+balance reagent acylated residue"}, {"accession": "MOD:00425", "name": "monohydroxylated residue"}, {"accession": "MOD:00397", "name": "iodoacetamide derivatized residue"}], "publications": [{"terms": [{"accession": "MS:1000879", "name": "PubMed identifier", "value": "28154077"}, {"accession": "PRIDE:0000400", "name": "Reference", "value": "Diering GH, Nirujogi RS, Roth RH, Worley PF, Pandey A, Huganir RL. Homer1a drives homeostatic scaling-down of excitatory synapses during sleep. Science. 2017 Feb 3;355(6324):511-515"}]}], "species": [{"terms": [{"accession": "MS:1001469", "name": "taxonomy: scientific name", "value": "Mus musculus (Mouse)"}, {"accession": "MS:1001467", "name": "taxonomy: NCBI TaxID", "value": "10090"}]}], "title": "Homer1a drives Homeostatic Scaling-down of Excitatory Synapses During Sleep"}